4","1639":"1639","1559":"1559","Hipperholme, Yorkshire, England":"Hipperholme, Yorkshire, England","Everingham, Yorkshire, England":"Everingham, Yorkshire, England","Goxhill, Lincolnshire, England":"Goxhill, Lincolnshire, England","Halifax, Yorkshire, England":"Halifax, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1559–1639":"1559–1639","1560–1644":"1560–1644","1577–1653":"1577–1653","1578–Male":"1578–Deceased","1580–1650":"1580–1650","1546–1568":"1546–1568","1544–1634":"1544–1634","1571":"1571","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","1569":"1569","1634":"1634","1568":"1568","1546":"1546","11 July 1568":"11 July 1568","1578":"1578","1600":"1600","1644":"1644","1577":"1577","1544":"1544","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1653":"1653","1585":"1585","1650":"1650","8 June 1634":"8 June 1634","1639":"1639","1559":"1559","Hipperholme, Yorkshire, England":"Hipperholme, Yorkshire, England","Everingham, Yorkshire, England":"Everingham, Yorkshire, England","Goxhill, Lincolnshire, England":"Goxhill, Lincolnshire, England","Halifax, Yorkshire, England":"Halifax, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wilson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name   Will   + patronymic <i>-son</i> ‘son of <i>Will</i>’. <i>Will</i> was a very common medieval short form of   William  . This surname is also very common among African Americans."],"variants":[{"name":"Willison","meanings":["English: variant of   Wilson  ."]},{"name":"Will","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Will</i>, a short form of   William  . This surname is now commonly found in Scotland, in Aberdeenshire, Angus, and Kincardineshire.","English: topographic name for someone who lived by a spring or stream, from Middle English <i>wel</i>, <i>wel(l)e</i>, <i>wille</i>, in a southwestern dialect form. This surname is found predominantly in the south and southwestern parts of the country. Compare   Well   1.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>iwil</i>, <i>wil(l)e</i> ‘agreeable, pleasing’."]},{"name":"Willson","meanings":["English (eastern): variant of   Wilson  ."]}]},{"name":"Rosalyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of   Rosalind .  <i>Rosalin</i> was a common medieval form, since the letters <i>d</i> and <i>t</i> were often added or dropped capriciously at the end of words after <i>n</i>. The name has been further influenced by the productive suffix <i>-lyn</i> (  see  Lynn  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rosalynn","meanings":["Altered form of   Rosalind .  <i>Rosalin</i> was a common medieval form, since the letters <i>d</i> and <i>t</i> were often added or dropped capriciously at the end of words after <i>n</i>. The name has been further influenced by the productive suffix <i>-lyn</i> (  see  Lynn  )."]},{"name":"Rosalynne","meanings":["Altered form of   Rosalind .  <i>Rosalin</i> was a common medieval form, since the letters <i>d</i> and <i>t</i> were often added or dropped capriciously at the end of words after <i>n</i>. The name has been further influenced by the productive suffix <i>-lyn</i> (  see  Lynn  )."]},{"name":"Rosaleen","meanings":["Variant of   Rosalyn  , influenced by the suffix <i>-een</i> (in origin the Irish Gaelic diminutive <i>-ín</i>). ‘Dark Rosaleen’ was the title of a poem by  James Clarence Mangan  (  1803–49 ), based on the Gaelic poem Róisín Dubh; in it the name is used as a figurative allusion to the Irish nation."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705205,"age":10,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":12,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":26,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":28,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":41,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":61,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.the